# ddoc
`ddoc` syncs Markdown files in GitHub repos to Confluence. Docs live next to code, get reviewed in PRs, and sync automatically after merge to the repo's default branch.

Official docs:
- [ddoc](https://datadoghq.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ODP/pages/6183815156/ddoc)
- [ddoc Syntax Reference](https://datadoghq.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ODP/pages/6197969213/ddoc+Syntax+Reference)

## Default workflow
1. Add ddoc frontmatter to a Markdown file once.
2. Review and merge changes to the repo's default branch, usually `main`.
3. Let `ddoc-sync-consumer` update Confluence.

Use the CLI for one-time setup, local validation, previews, and manual syncs. In steady state, publish docs by merging PRs.

## Installation
Recommended on Apple Silicon:

```shell
dogbrew install ddoc
```

Homebrew alternative:

```shell
brew update && brew install datadog/tap/ddoc
```

When switching from Homebrew to Dogbrew, uninstall the Homebrew version first:

```shell
brew uninstall datadog/tap/ddoc
```

Run from `dd-source` without installing:

```shell
bzl run //domains/odp/apps/apis/ddoc-sync-consumer/cmd/ddoc -- sync <path>
```

## Authentication and environment
`sync`, `status`, and verified `link` need Confluence credentials:

```shell
export CONFLUENCE_EMAIL='you@datadoghq.com'
export CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN='your-atlassian-api-token'
export CONFLUENCE_URL='https://datadoghq.atlassian.net'
export DDOC_DEFAULT_SPACE='ODP'
```

Rules:
- Never hardcode or print `CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN` or `CONFLUENCE_TOKEN`.
- `CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN` and `CONFLUENCE_TOKEN` are both accepted.
- `CONFLUENCE_EMAIL` and `CONFLUENCE_USERNAME` are both accepted.
- `CONFLUENCE_URL` defaults to `https://datadoghq.atlassian.net`.
- `DDOC_DEFAULT_SPACE` only applies when frontmatter omits `confluence_space`.
- `ddoc check` is offline-friendly. It uses credentials, when present, only to detect page conflicts.

## Common commands
| Command | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `ddoc init FILE --space SPACE` | Add ddoc frontmatter. Optional: `--parent`, `--title`, `--emoji`, `--width`. |
| `ddoc link FILE PAGE_ID` | Link a file to an existing Confluence page and write `confluence_id`. |
| `ddoc check PATH [PATH ...]` | Validate frontmatter and conversion without writing. |
| `ddoc status [path ...]` | Show sync status against Confluence without writing. |
| `ddoc sync [path ...]` | Preview, confirm, and sync pages. |
| `ddoc version` | Print the CLI version. |

Useful `sync` flags:
- `--dry-run`: preview only.
- `-y` / `--yes`: skip confirmation, usually for CI.
- `--force`: re-push unchanged pages and skip confirmation.

Flags can appear before or after positional arguments.

## Onboarding docs
### Link an existing Confluence page
Copy the page ID from a URL like `.../pages/<ID>/...`, then run:

```shell
ddoc link docs/architecture.md 6183815156
```

Commit the frontmatter change. Future merges to the default branch update that page.

### Create a new Confluence page
When no page exists yet:

```shell
ddoc init docs/runbook.md --space ODP --parent 1234567890
ddoc sync docs/runbook.md
```

The first sync creates the page and writes `confluence_id` to the file. Commit that ID.

### Preview selected files

```shell
ddoc sync --dry-run docs/
ddoc sync --dry-run src/pawprints/*.md
```

## Frontmatter
Every managed Markdown file starts with YAML frontmatter:

```yaml
---
ddoc:
  confluence_id: "6183815156"
  confluence_space: "ODP"
  confluence_parent: "1234567890"
  title: "My Page Title"
  emoji: "🚀"
  width: full-width
  banner: false
  exclude: true
---
```

Field rules:
- Specify at least `confluence_id` or `confluence_space`.
- `confluence_id` updates an existing page. Without it, ddoc creates a page.
- `confluence_space` is required for new pages and whenever `confluence_parent` is set.
- `confluence_parent` sets the parent page ID for child pages.
- `title` overrides the first H1 as the Confluence page title.
- `emoji` sets the Confluence page icon.
- `width` accepts `default` or `full-width`. Unset preserves the current Confluence width.
- `banner` defaults to `true`. Set `false` to hide the source banner.
- `exclude: true` skips the file during sync.

## Page organization
### Directory of pages
Each annotated file becomes one page. Child pages can declare `confluence_parent`. An `index.md` automatically becomes the parent for sibling files in the same directory.

### Split one file into pages
Use inline directives:

```markdown
# Parent Page Title

Parent content.

<!-- ddoc:page "API Reference" id:1234567 emoji:📘 -->

## API Reference

Child page content.

<!-- ddoc:page-end -->

Back to parent content.
```

Directive notes:
- `<!-- ddoc:page "Title" -->` starts a child page.
- Add `id:PAGE_ID` to update an existing page instead of creating a duplicate.
- Add `emoji:EMOJI` to set a child page icon.
- `<!-- ddoc:page-end -->` returns content to the parent page.

## Ignore content
Hide content from Confluence while keeping it in GitHub:

```markdown
<!-- ddoc:ignore -->
This next line is hidden from Confluence.

<!-- ddoc:ignore:start -->
This block is hidden from Confluence.
<!-- ddoc:ignore:end -->
```

ddoc also strips common CI/CD badges.

## Supported Markdown and Confluence features
Use normal GitHub-Flavored Markdown when possible. ddoc supports:
- Fenced code blocks, with language aliases such as `js`, `ts`, `py`, `sh`, `shell`, and `yml` normalized for Confluence.
- Mermaid diagrams from ```mermaid fences. ddoc renders them with `mmdc` when available and falls back to code blocks otherwise.
- GFM callouts: `> [!NOTE]`, `> [!TIP]`, `> [!WARNING]`, `> [!IMPORTANT]`, `> [!CAUTION]`.
- Bold-prefix callouts: `> **Note:**`, `> **Warning:**`, `> **Tip:**`.
- Tables, task lists, strikethrough, images, and local image uploads as Confluence attachments.
- Status lozenges: `{status:green|Done}`, `{status:yellow|In Progress}`, `{status:red|Blocked}`, `{status:blue|Info}`, `{status:grey|Skipped}`.
- Table of contents macros: `[TOC]` or `[[_TOC_]]`.
- `<details>/<summary>` converted to Confluence expand macros.
- Links to other ddoc-managed `.md` files rewritten to Confluence page URLs.

For Mermaid support:

```shell
npm install -g @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli
```

Optional Mermaid environment:
- `DDOC_DIAGRAM_DIR`: diagram PNG cache directory. Default: `/tmp/ddoc/diagrams`.
- `DDOC_MERMAID_CLI`: path to `mmdc`. Default: auto-detected.

## Validation before push
Prefer this sequence before committing ddoc changes:

```shell
ddoc check README.md docs/architecture.md
ddoc status docs/
ddoc sync --dry-run docs/
```

Use `ddoc check` for fast offline validation. Use `status` or `sync --dry-run` to compare against Confluence when credentials are available.

## Auto-sync requirements
Auto-sync runs only when:
- the repo is in the `DataDog` GitHub org,
- the repo has a `dd-octo-sts` policy,
- the push is on the repo's default branch, and
- the changed `.md` file has ddoc frontmatter.

## Safety guidance
- Do not edit ddoc-managed pages directly in Confluence. Edit the source Markdown in GitHub.
- After `ddoc sync` creates a page and writes `confluence_id`, commit the frontmatter update.
- Use `id:PAGE_ID` for existing inline child pages to avoid duplicates.
- Prefer `--dry-run`, `ddoc check`, and `ddoc status` before manual writes.
- Do not use `--force` unless the user needs to re-push unchanged content.
- ddoc attempts to preserve Confluence inline comment markers when the marked text still exists.

